Framingham Study Plots

The Framingham Heart Study is a long term prospective study of the etiology of cardiovascular disease among a population of free living subjects in the community of Framingham, Massachusetts. The Framingham Heart Study was a landmark study in epidemiology in that it was the first prospective study of cardiovascular disease and identified the concept of risk factors and their joint effects. The study began in 1948 and 5,209 subjects were initially enrolled in the study.

In this analysis there will some plots about this study and considerations about health behaviors based on this dataset.

Ask

Scenario

Cardiovascular diseases are a major burden for the Global Healthcare market and the Framingham Heart Study build a dataset with variables related to this disease.

Main Analysis Task

What is the relationship between the BMI (Body Mass Index) variable and the heart diseases?

Prepare

About the Framingham Heart Study dataset

The enclosed dataset is a subset of the data collected as part of the Framingham study and includes laboratory, clinic, questionnaire, and adjudicated event data on 4,434 participants. Participant clinic data was collected during three examination periods, approximately 6 years apart, from roughly 1956 to 1968. Each participant was followed for a total of 24 years for the outcome of the following events: Angina Pectoris, Myocardial Infarction, Atherothrombotic Infarction or Cerebral Hemorrhage (Stroke) or death. (NOTE: Although the enclosed dataset contains Framingham data ‘as collected’ by Framingham investigators, specific methods were employed to ensure an anonymous dataset that protects patient confidentiality; therefore, this dataset is inappropriate for publication purposes).

Evaluation of ROCCC

  • Reliable - Data is reliable and it was collected using the best practices in the time of collection.
  • Original - The data is original and was produced in the community of Framingham, Massachusetts.
  • Comprehensive - The data is comprehensive with many important variables
  • Current - Participant clinic data was collected during three examination periods, approximately 6 years apart, from roughly 1956 to 1968. Each participant was followed for a total of 24 years.
  • Cited – The data is very important and has been cited and used many times by various analysts.

Summary of the Analysis

1. Participants Health

Hypothesis:

  • Persons with higher BMI has more chance to develop a heart condition
  • A balanced BMI improve the health condition of a person thus avoid the development of an disease heart condition.
  • The lower BMI also is related with a lower prevalence of Stroke.

Consolidated plots

Slide 1!
Slide 2!
Slide 3!

Conclusion:

The plots confirm our hypothesis and shows that a controlled BMI prevents not only the occurrence of heart diseases but in addition diabetes and strokes.

Age also is related with a higher risk of development chronic diseases.

Analysis next steps

  • Conduct a machine learning analysis to predict the occurrence of the diseases.

Act

Recommendations to improve the population Heart health condition.

By analyzing the Framingham Heart Study dataset we can conclude the following main points:

  • Individuals must lower their BMI in order to prevent heart diseases.

  • The chronic diseases burden of CVD, stroke and diabetes will decrease if public programs of health care focus on the balance of population BMI.

  • Older persons have a tendency to develop heart diseases, diabetes and stroke thus they demands an even more controlled BMI

Reference:

  • Framingham Heart Study
